message: Don’t be sorry at all for telling me. My dad passed away on September 4, 2015 so unfortunately I know the feeling all too well. There are no words to adequately respond, express, address any of it. It isn’t fair and I’m so sorry you have to experience this. Take your time, do what you need to do to process and grieve and be. Just know I’ve been down this road and I am here if you need anything at all. Please take care of yourself.
I’ll write you soon.
That was a weird thing to tell you. I’m sorry.
My mother passed away today.
Hi. I’m sorry I didn’t respond earlier. I owe you a long response. I wrote one months ago. I’ll send it to you soon.
Hi
Is there an award for longest tinder messages? We would totally win.

My ideal date? As in money is not an object? Well then it obviously involves a private jet and you taking me to all the best places you’ve seen. If I’m being more money cautious then I’d love to sit on Emma Rose and watch you work on the motor. I feel like you’d probably curse and things but I’d have some coffee and enjoy. And cheer you on of course. Thinking even simpler I love watching movies and eating snacks so anything combing those and I’m a cheap date. Not hard to please.

If I’m being honest, I’m usually a ball of nerves all the time but I’m great at hiding it. I live by the phrase “fake it till you make it” and so far its worked out for me in a lot of aspects of my life.
It is the worst how bachelor/bachelorette weekends take up the entire weekend! We will never put our wedding party through it.

Wow, seems like you’ve got a lot to do to keep you busy. But that’s good about side projects that you actually enjoy. There’s not enough time to waste it doing something that you’re not intrinsically motivated about and extremely passionate for. So I’m all for you doing whatever will lead you to that bliss. Sorry to get super cheesy on you I just reflect a lot as it’s kind of viral to my job and how effective I am as a teacher each day. And in all my reflections I realize how beyond lucky I am to love what I do and get such joy from it. I want everyone in the world to experience that feeling. All of your travel sounds incredible and don’t worry I’m not so good at selling myself either. If it’s not already been made clear I literally spend all of any free time I have left thinking and striving to be better for the little minds I’m teaching. Most of my money goes to my classroom and I couldn’t be happier about it.

I have no thoughts* on bachelorette parties. I’ve never attended one. I’ve been to a few out of town bachelor parties and I dislike how they consume an entire weekend. I don’t think think I would ever subject my friends to an exotic destination either. 
Sounds like you went on a classic bad first date. Were either of you nervous / do you ever get nervous on dates? I tend to sporadically feel nervous (inter, not intra) on dates and have a lot of trouble convincing people I like that I am worthy of them. (again, terrible job of selling myself).  Anyway … what do you like to do on first dates? Do ever plan activities or … what would you do / where would you go on your ideal first date?

Hi Mar! Sorry for my late response. There was so much text to respond to. I hope you had a good weekend. 
What about me? I just realized that I never fully told you what I do. I co-founded a small, unsuccessful, boutique hedge fund based in New York, Menlo Park (SF bay area), and Luxembourg. It's kind of terrible. I also spend about 1 0% of my time with the coffee NGO I spoke to you about before and I independently consult for UNICEF (~ a few hours per month). I also manage a micro-vc fund that I’m the only LP in. My side projects help keep me sane. 
At some point (hopefully by next winter) I’m going to quit my job and spend more time working on side projects and doing things for myself. I would like to spend next winter skiing in Chamonix, Verbier, or even Hakuba. After my sabbatical I might go back to graduate school. My life and my future plans are both messes and not conducive to building stable relationships. I’m doing a really terrible job of selling myself.  
I have no though...
Looking forward to stealing your boat

The disastrous date was just your standard first date when two people are on two completely different wavelengths and can’t figure out how the hell it make it work. So many awkward silences, followed by many awkward gulps of my wine.

Traveling extensively hasn’t been something I have thought long and hard about. Summers in the past have been trials and tribulations of job interviews and demo lessons and subsequent rejection letters so now I hardly know what to do with myself with the time off. Last summer was god awful because I was a bridesmaid in 3 weddings. All of which invoked extensive out of town bachelorette parties. I will never put our bridal party through that. I was so excited for school to start back up again and dive back into something I am passionate about that has purpose. I love my job and I know how lucky I am to be able to say that. What about you? Thoughts towards your job? Bachelorette parties?

I have absolutely no interest in a polyamorous relationship. Call me crazy but I want someone who thinks the sun rises and sets with me because I’m a pretty great catch. (I also thrive on codependence and affection).

The kids I teach are in first grade so they’re 6 year olds tinder is a nonissue in my room. Don’t worry though- I make my kids was there hands a lot throughout the day. I don’t have any time for sticky hands. I have to teach them how to read!
Hi! Sorry for the late response - you didn’t overwhelm me! Just extra elusive during the week
And can you grade my stream of consciousness, loose collection of semi-coherent thoughts? I tried my hardest to spell and conjugate everything correctly.

What do you do over the summer? Have you thought about traveling extensively? One of my engineers spent part of his vacation as a farmer in Oregon and another learned Kung Fu for three weeks in a Shaolin Monastery in the Kunyu Mountains. I sailed around scandinavia and spent a week working remotely from a beach in the Canary islands. Which countries did you take your kids to? Did they enjoy traveling? Can we leave our kids at home when we travel? My parents brought me everywhere with them when I was young (which I am very thankful for) and in return, I was a monster. I don’t know how they put up with me. 
Can you tell me about your disastrous date? Finally, I hope I haven’t overwhelmed you. If so, I apologize. Also, how do you feel about surprise weddings?

Boats: I have spent more time cleaning and fixing my boat than I have spent sailing it. My apartment is littered with random boat parts. My outboard (I also have an inboard) motor is sitting on my tiny kitchen table in new york in 30 pieces. I have to replace the main sail, all of the sheets, redo the cushions, replace most of the electrical, update the refrigerator. One day I spent 10 hours cleaning the bathroom and the bedroom while heavily rocking. It was also fantastic. It’s dry docked now but starting April 1st, you’ll be able to find it at the pier 40 Marina off W. Houston. It’s named the Emma Rose. I keep it unlocked because I’m an idiot. You’re welcome to steal it.
sexual partners* (I’m weird). I probably wouldn’t seek other partners if my partner was poly. I’m not sure if it would work.

Are you interested in polyamorous relationships? My last relationship ended (in 2014) when the person I wanted to spend the rest of my life with said that she wanted to be polyamorous and I said that it would make me uncomfortable, and then she started sleeping with her roommate anyway. We were friends for four years before we started dating and we were together for nearly two years. When she dumped me, we were interning at the same company. The rest of that summer was indescribably fantastic. Especially because of how close our desks were to each other. I’ve read a few books on polyamory including The Ethical Slut, More Than Two, and Opening Up and I think the concept has merit in theory, but there’s a lot of heartbreak in practice (most of the books on the subject are about how to avoid heartbreak). At some point in my life, I wouldn’t be opposed to trying it, but I care more about emotional connection, value alignment, and support than I do about having multiple sexual partners (...

I am terrible with children. I am barely keeping my life together and would have trouble looking out for someone else’s best interests. I also dislike when little kids have sticky hands. As a desperately single, unstable (non compos mentis) person that’s barely capable of existing in civil society, I seek acceptance, affection, and co-dependence. I’ve often thought about getting a dog for those reasons. It would love me until it died from starvation / gross negligence.
